def features_categorical(df,name):
    ''' 
    The function will find Percentage of Unique values per each categorical column for data set
    '''
    print("List of Categorical for", name ," dataset :\n")
    percent_uniquevaluesper_column = df[list(df.select_dtypes(include=['object']))].nunique()/len(df) * 100
    percent_uniquevaluesper_column.sort_values(ascending=False).plot(kind="bar",figsize=(20,5))
    plt.title("Percentage of Unique values per each column")
    plt.xlabel('Column Name')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage of Unique values')
    plt.show()
    for x in list(df.select_dtypes(include=['object'])):
        if (df[x].nunique() < 10):
            uniquelist = df[x].unique()
            print("- ",x,":", df[x].nunique()," and list of unique values that are less than 10 : ", uniquelist)

# Data assessing
def assesing_df(df):
    ''' 
    The function will assess dataset as following:
    - Number of rows and columns 
    - Distribution of percentage of missing values.
    - Applying decribe function for dataset.
    - Percentage of missing values per each colum.
    - List of columns have more than 20% Missing Values.
    - Percentage of Missing Values in Rows
    - features_categorical
    '''
     
    name =[x for x in globals() if globals()[x] is df][0]
    # Print rows and columns in dataset
    print( "Size of", name, ": \n"
          "number of rows: ",df.shape[0],"\n"
          "number of columns: ",df.shape[1])
    # Describ
    print(df.describe(include='all'))
    # Assess null values
    #Distribution of percentage of missing values in each column
    percent_missing_per_column =(df.isnull().sum()/len(df)*100)
    percent_missing_per_column.hist(bins=10,xlabelsize=8)
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.title("Distribution of percentage of missing values in each column")
    plt.ylabel('Number of Columns')
    plt.xlabel('Percentage of Missing Values in Columns')
    plt.show()
    #Percentage of missing values per each column
    percent_missing_per_column.plot(kind="bar", figsize=(20,5))
    plt.title("Percentage of missing values per each column")
    plt.xlabel('Column Name')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage of Missing Values')
    #List of columns have more than 20% Missing Values
    outliers  = percent_missing_per_column[percent_missing_per_column>20]
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()
    if len(outliers) == 0 :
        print('\n There are not columns that have more than 20% Missing Values')
    else:
        outliers.sort_values(ascending=False).plot(kind="bar")
        plt.title("List of columns have more than 20% Missing Values")
        plt.xlabel("Column name")
        plt.ylabel("Number of missing values")
        plt.grid(True)
        plt.show()
    #Percentage of Missing Values in Rows
    percent_missing_val_row = df.isnull().sum(axis=1)/(len(df.columns)) * 100
    plt.hist(percent_missing_val_row, bins=10, facecolor='b', alpha=0.75)
    plt.xlabel('Percentage of Missing Values')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.ylabel('Number of Rows')
    plt.title('Percentage of Missing Values in Rows')
    plt.show()
    features_categorical(df,name)

Findings¶

Based on the result mentioned above for listings dataset,it seems like there will be data prep and cleansing required to use this dataset for business questions. We should convert the price variables to numeric and drop the unnecessary variables and convert some nessoray columns to boolean variable. The experiences offered are None for all rows. The host_location column can use some standardization if we are to use it for analysis. For example: "Berlin / Müggelsdorf", "Berlin, Deutschland" and "Neukölln, Berlin, Germany" should be considered as the same.

This amenities column contains a list of values in each row. In order to handle the amenities column, we will try to understand which are some of the most common amenities that are present within the listings. Once we know which amenities are important, we will create additional columns to represent each amenity as a boolean field.

#Remove Dollar
def remove_dollar(column_name, df):
    df[column_name] = df[column_name].str.replace('$','').str.replace(',','')
    df[column_name].fillna(0, inplace=True)
In [10]:
#Remove Numeric
def make_numeric(column_name, df):
    df[column_name] = pd.to_numeric(df[column_name])
In [11]:
def make_boolean(column_name, df):
    df[column_name] = df[column_name] == 't'

def make_datetype(column_name, df):
    df[column_name] = pd.to_datetime(df[column_name])

def price_analysis_monthly(df):
    # Plot the average price by month/year 
    df['year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df['date']).year
    df['month'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df['date']).month
    mean_price_monthly = df.groupby(['year','month'],sort=False)['price'].mean()
    plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 18})
    mean_price_monthly.plot(kind = 'barh' , figsize = (30,10));
    plt.show()
In [17]:
price_analysis_monthly(calendar)

Findings¶

The graph above shows us how the mean prices change over the year. We have noticed that September and May are the peak months. Since the weather during these months in Berlin is always good, it makes sense that prices in these months are higher compared to others.

def price_analysis_neighbourhood_count(df):
    listings.groupby(['neighbourhood_cleansed'])[['price']].mean().plot(figsize=(30,10))
    plt.show()
    neighbourhood_count = pd.DataFrame()
    neighbourhood_count['count'] = listings['neighbourhood_cleansed'].value_counts()
    neighbourhood_mean = pd.DataFrame()
    neighbourhood_mean['mean_price'] = listings.groupby(listings['neighbourhood_cleansed'])['price'].mean()
    neighbourhood_info = pd.merge(neighbourhood_mean, neighbourhood_count, left_on = neighbourhood_mean.index,right_on = neighbourhood_count.index)
    neighbourhood_info.index = neighbourhood_info.key_0
    plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 12})
    neighbourhood_info.sort_values(by = 'mean_price', ascending=False).head(5).plot(kind = 'barh',figsize = (15,10))
    plt.show()
    plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 12})
    neighbourhood_info.sort_values(by = 'mean_price', ascending=False).tail(5).plot(kind = 'barh',figsize = (15,10))
    plt.show()

Findings¶

From the charts above, we have noticed that the neighbourhoods of Forst Grunewald, Volkspark Wilmersdorf and Allende-Viertel have highest mean price with 200 dollar and 400 dollar , while the neighbourhoods of Neu-Hohenschönhausen, Hellersdorf-süd have lowest mean prices with around $ 25.

Similarily we see that the neighbourhoods of Alexanderplatz and Schöneberg-Nord have highest listing counts, while neighbourhoods of Forst-Grunewald and Neu-Hohenschönhausen have lower listing counts

3.3 Is it possile to make an accurate predictive model for listing price based on machine leraning¶

# Cleansing dataset for predictive model¶

Based on assesing charts above for listings data we decided to clean as following:

  • drop columns that have less impact, For example: 'id','listing_url','scrape_id','last_scraped','thumbnail_url','medium_url','xl_picture_url','host_id','host_url', 'host_thumbnail_url','host_verifications','street','neighbourhood','neighbourhood_group_cleansed','zipcode','smart_location', 'country','latitude','longitude','weekly_price','monthly_price','calendar_updated','calendar_last_scraped','first_review', 'last_review','calculated_host_listings_count','reviews_per_month','jurisdiction_names', 'host_acceptance_rate', 'name','summary','space','description','experiences_offered','neighborhood_overview','notes','transit','access','house_rules', 'picture_url','market','host_response_time','state','license','host_name', 'host_location', 'host_about', 'host_picture_url','interaction','require_guest_profile_picture' , 'require_guest_phone_verification' , 'host_since' and 'host_neighbourhood'.

  • Set 0 for bathroom where bathroom is Nan.

  • Set 1 for bedrooms where bedrooms is Nan.
  • Set 1 for beds where beds is Nan.
  • Set all review scores columns with 0 for Nan values.
  • Set host_listings_count and host_total_listings_count to 1.
  • Set host_response_rate to 0 for Nan values and convert to numric
  • Clean security_deposit, cleaning_fee and extra people.
  • Clean up city name.
  • Drop record with empty value for cancellation_policy and host_since.
  • we take only those amenities that are present more than 11000 times , which are below. ('Wifi', 23347), ('Heating', 22990), ('Kitchen', 22904), ('Essentials', 22242), ('Washer', 19834), ('Hair dryer', 16680), ('Laptop friendly workspace', 16072), ('Hangers', 15714), ('Iron', 12682), ('Shampoo', 11814), ('Hot water', 11394), ('TV', 11068)
In [20]:
def handle_amenities(df_list):
    # Handle amenities - Explore most common amenities
    amenities = []
    for index, row in df_list.iterrows():
        row['amenities'] = row['amenities'].replace('{','')
        row['amenities'] = row['amenities'].replace('}','')
        row['amenities'] = row['amenities'].replace('"','')
        mylist = row['amenities'].split(',')
        for l in mylist:
            amenities.append(l)

    amenities_count = Counter(amenities)
    amenities_count.most_common()
    amenities_new_cols =['amenities_wifi|Wifi',
     'amenities_heating|Heating',
     'amenities_kitchen|Kitchen',
     'amenities_essentials|Essentials',
     'amenities_washer|Washer',
     'amenities_hair_dryer|Hair dryer',
     'amenities_laptop_friendly_workspace|Laptop friendly workspace',
     'amenities_hangers|Hangers',
     'amenities_iron|Iron',
     'amenities_shampoo|Shampoo',
     'amenities_hot_water|Hot water',
     'amenities_TV|TV']
    for c in amenities_new_cols:
        c_colname,c_desc = c.split('|')
        df_list[c_colname] = df_list['amenities'].apply(lambda x: 1 if c_desc in x else 0)
    # Drop the original amenities field
    df_list = df_list.drop('amenities', axis = 1)
    return df_list

def cleaning_for_predictions(listings):
    df_list = listings.copy()
    cols_less_impact = ['id','listing_url','scrape_id','last_scraped','thumbnail_url','medium_url','xl_picture_url','host_id',
                        'host_url','host_thumbnail_url','host_verifications','street','neighbourhood',
                        'neighbourhood_group_cleansed','zipcode','smart_location','country','latitude','longitude',
                        'weekly_price','monthly_price','calendar_updated','calendar_last_scraped','first_review','last_review',
                        'calculated_host_listings_count','reviews_per_month','jurisdiction_names',
                        'host_acceptance_rate','square_feet']
    df_list = df_list.drop(cols_less_impact, axis=1)
    col_isnull = df_list.columns[df_list.isnull().all()].tolist()
    df_list = df_list.drop(col_isnull, axis=1)
    # Set 0 for bathroom where bathroom is Nan
    df_list['bathrooms'] = df_list['bathrooms'].fillna(0)
    # Set 1 for bedrooms where bedrooms is Nan
    df_list['bedrooms'] = df_list['bedrooms'].fillna(1)
    # Set 1 for beds where beds is Nan
    df_list['beds'] = df_list['beds'].fillna(1)
    # Set all review scores columns with 0 for Nan values
    cols_fillna_0 = ['review_scores_rating','review_scores_accuracy','review_scores_cleanliness','review_scores_checkin','review_scores_communication','review_scores_location','review_scores_value']
    for col in cols_fillna_0:
        df_list[col] = df_list[col].fillna(0)
    # Set host_listings_count and host_total_listings_count to 1
    df_list['host_listings_count'] = df_list['host_listings_count'].fillna(1)
    df_list['host_total_listings_count'] = df_list['host_total_listings_count'].fillna(1)
    tf_fields = ['host_is_superhost','host_has_profile_pic','host_identity_verified','is_location_exact','has_availability','requires_license',
                'instant_bookable','is_business_travel_ready']
    for t in tf_fields:
        df_list[t] = df_list[t].apply(set_bool_tf)
    drop_list = ['name','summary','space','description','experiences_offered','neighborhood_overview','notes','transit','access','house_rules','picture_url','market','host_response_time','state','license','host_name', 'host_location', 'host_about', 'host_picture_url','interaction','require_guest_profile_picture', 'require_guest_phone_verification']
    df_list = df_list.drop(drop_list, axis = 1)
    
    df_list['host_response_rate'] = df_list['host_response_rate'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == 'N/A' else x)
    df_list['host_response_rate'] = df_list['host_response_rate'].replace('[\%,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)
    df_list['host_response_rate'] = df_list['host_response_rate'].fillna(0)
    
    #df_list['host_neighbourhood'] = df_list['host_neighbourhood'].fillna('N/A')
  
    # Clean security_deposit, cleaning_fee and extra people
    df_list['security_deposit'] = df_list['security_deposit'].replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)
    df_list['cleaning_fee'] = df_list['cleaning_fee'].replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)
    df_list['extra_people'] = df_list['extra_people'].replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)
    df_list['security_deposit'] = df_list['security_deposit'].fillna(0)
    df_list['cleaning_fee'] = df_list['cleaning_fee'].fillna(0)
    # Clean up city names
    df_list['city'] = df_list['city'].fillna('berlin')
    df_list['city'] = df_list['city'].str.lower()
    df_list['city'] = df_list['city'].str.strip()
    # Drop record with empty value for cancellation_policy and host_since.
    df_list = df_list.dropna(subset=['cancellation_policy','host_since'], axis=0)
    make_datetype('host_since',listings)
    df_list['host_since_year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df_list['host_since']).year
    df_list['host_since_year_month'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df_list['host_since']).month
    df_list = df_list.drop(['host_since','host_neighbourhood'], axis = 1)
    df_list = handle_amenities(df_list)
    return df_list

In [45]:
def coef_weights(coefficients, X_train):
    '''
    Function to get coefficients back for each of the features
    INPUT:
    coefficients - the coefficients of the linear model 
    X_train - the training data, so the column names can be used
    OUTPUT:
    coefs_df - a dataframe holding the coefficient, estimate, and abs(estimate)
    
    Provides a dataframe that can be used to understand the most influential coefficients
    in a linear model by providing the coefficient estimates along with the name of the 
    variable attached to the coefficient.
    '''
    coefs_df = pd.DataFrame()
    coefs_df['est_int'] = X_train.columns
    coefs_df['coefs'] = coefficients.feature_importances_
    coefs_df['abs_coefs'] = np.abs(coefficients.feature_importances_)
    coefs_df = coefs_df.sort_values('abs_coefs', ascending=False)
    return coefs_df
